d know how her playful and heart-felt video delivery carries through to her good-for-you-and-the-planet recipes \u0026mdash; now encapsulated in her first cookbook, \u003ca href=\"https://amzn.to/48t4Z2g\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eJOYFULL: Cook Effortlessly, Eat Freely, Live Radiantly\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/a\u003e. The trained dietitian, nutritionist and Ayurvedic student approaches a passion for holistic well-being anyone can tap into, leaning into everything from smoothies designed to bring more vitality into your body and day (Iron Beet-Down) to \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/sleep-moon-milk/\"\u003eMoon Milks\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003e that help you wind down, to familial favourite mains (Momma\u0026rsquo;s Rich and Creamy Three-Bean Red Curry and Baa\u0026rsquo;s Wedding Daal). And of course, there are desserts.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eRadhi also lays the groundwork for understanding how she mindfully chooses her ingredients and how each works to heal and support your overall well-being. We caught up with Radhi to dive deeper into \u003cem\u003eJOYFULL\u003c/em\u003e, what fuels her and why she avoids cooking with garlic (and onions). Read on for the full interview.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eRadhi\u0026rsquo;s \u003ca href=\"https://amzn.to/48t4Z2g\"\u003ecookbook\u003c/a\u003e is\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003e\u0026nbsp;now available on Amazon and in bookstores everywhere.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eIn \u003cem\u003eJOYFULL\u003c/em\u003e, you approach food in a holistic 360-degree way. How did you come to this view?\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eSo I grew up in an Indian family where my mom was the most magnificent cook. She worked a full-time job, but she made sure that we had amazing breakfasts, lunches and dinners every single day. And that in itself was such a beautiful inspiration for me growing up. She would experiment with different flavours from our Indian background. There was always such emphasis on spices. I also grew up a vegetarian. And so everything was based around vegetables and lentils, beans and pulses; it was just so colourful, vibrant and always so delicious. So, she was probably my first inspiration.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eThen after that, my mom actually recommended that I get a nutrition degree. All I knew at that time was that I loved eating. I had a zest for watching my mom cook and helping her. So I did my nutrition and dietetics degree. I learned so much about the breakdown of food, and how it affects your body. It was such a good foundation for me to see the Western way of approaching nutrition.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRelated: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/inspiring-cookbooks-by-black-authors/\"\u003eInspiring Cookbooks by Black Authors to Add to Your Bookshelf\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eThen I moved to New York, which I had to do because my husband [author and podcast host Jay Shetty] got a job [there]. At the time, I actually couldn\u0026rsquo;t work so I decided to throw myself into study. So I studied Ayurveda, I did my yoga teacher training there, and it brought me a whole new perspective [on] how I grew up and how my mom used spices to heal me.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003e[I learned] just how easy it is to nourish your body through what nature provides us with. How to actually get nutrients that benefit not just our body, but how food can impact our consciousness, mind and \u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003ejoy \u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003ein life. The book [\u003cem\u003eJOYFULL\u003c/em\u003e] is not an Ayurvedic book, but I have included the basic principles that I feel everybody, no matter where you\u0026rsquo;re from or what you do, can really benefit from.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRelated: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/immunity-cubes/\"\u003eMake These Immunity Cubes for Cold and Flu Season\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"attachment_150106\" style=\"width: 858px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-150106\" class=\"wp-image-150106 size-full\" src=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull.jpg\" alt=\"Radhi Devlukia-Shetty and her family having a picnic\" width=\"848\" height=\"565\" srcset=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull.jpg 848w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull.jpg?resize=300,200 300w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull.jpg?resize=768,512 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 848px) 100vw, 848px\"\u003e\u003cp id=\"caption-attachment-150106\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"\u003eAlanna Hale\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eYou already touched on this a little bit, but you also weave in how the role of your family has had on the recipes in \u003cem\u003eJOYFULL\u003c/em\u003e. Can you say a bit more about this?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eYou know, there\u0026rsquo;s something about food. And I talk about this in the book \u0026mdash; that it\u0026rsquo;s cooked with so much love. There\u0026rsquo;s something about [a] mother\u0026rsquo;s cooking. B\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eut it also comes down to so much deep intention while you\u0026rsquo;re cooking, right? When I became vegan, there was nothing I couldn\u0026rsquo;t eat because she would create and experiment with ingredients to make sure that we weren\u0026rsquo;t missing out on anything.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eThere\u0026rsquo;s such a beauty watching her and it made me realize, you know, nothing was ever a \u0026lsquo;no.\u0026rsquo; There was always a desire to keep experimenting, even though she already knew so much. \u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eI think to always be a student in the kitchen is a beautiful way to keep your food exciting, fun and vibrant.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRelated: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/moonglettes-savory-lentil-pancakes/\"\u003eRadhi Devlukia-Shetty\u0026rsquo;s Moonglettes (Savory Lentil Pancakes)\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat recipes are you most excited about in your cookbook? Which is your favourite?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eThere are so many different ones for different reasons and different seasons. The one I\u0026rsquo;m really happy I brought into the book for sentimental value is my grandma Baa\u0026rsquo;s [Wedding] Daal, which she\u0026rsquo;s been making since she started cooking when she was 13 years old. It\u0026rsquo;s a sweet and sour lentil dish and a lot runnier than normal curries or lentils, but it\u0026rsquo;s packed with \u003cem\u003eso\u003c/em\u003e much flavour.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRelated: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/comforting-daal-chawal/\"\u003eMake This Comforting Daal Chawal\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat are your top three favourite ingredients to work with?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eEvery single dish has some sort of spice in it because spices were a really important part of creating the book.\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003e I use cumin a lot, and I think that\u0026rsquo;s an easy one because it\u0026rsquo;s used in so many different cuisines. It\u0026rsquo;s used in \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/tag/indian/\"\u003eIndian food\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/tag/mexican/\"\u003eMexican food\u003c/a\u003e [and] Moroccan food. So it\u0026rsquo;s something that you may even have in your cupboard already.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eOne of the stronger ones that I really like is mustard seed. It definitely has a powerful taste, but it adds so much if you put it into oil; it\u0026rsquo;s really vibrant.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eThe third one is one that probably people wouldn\u0026rsquo;t know much about but it\u0026rsquo;s one that I use in my book a lot, and it\u0026rsquo;s called asafetida or hing. [You can use it in place of] or on top of onion and garlic, but it\u0026rsquo;s got so many health benefits. You need like an eighth of a teaspoon. That\u0026rsquo;s one that I\u0026rsquo;m excited to introduce people to because it adds so much. It has a very similar taste and flavour profile to onion or garlic in that intensity but it\u0026rsquo;s much kinder to your gut.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"attachment_150107\" style=\"width: 858px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-150107\" class=\"wp-image-150107 size-full\" src=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull-1.jpg\" alt=\"JOYFULL cookbook\" width=\"848\" height=\"565\" srcset=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull-1.jpg 848w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull-1.jpg?resize=300,200 300w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-gallery-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-joyfull-1.jpg?resize=768,512 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 848px) 100vw, 848px\"\u003e\u003cp id=\"caption-attachment-150107\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"\u003eJOYFULL: Cook Effortlessly, Eat Freely, Live Radiantly, $30, via Amazon\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eThose who may not be familiar with your recipes may be surprised to learn that you avoid onion and garlic. Can you say a bit more about this choice?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eYeah, for multiple reasons. When I studied Ayurveda, I found that every single food carries energy in how it affects the body. So the medicinal qualities of onion and garlic are so potent that they were used as medicine back in the day. But the problem is that we\u0026rsquo;ve taken these powerful ingredients and we\u0026rsquo;re using them every single day in every single meal \u0026mdash; so now it\u0026rsquo;s gone the opposite way. It\u0026rsquo;s actually causing inflammation in our body.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eBut the main reason was because I believe that there are so many other flavours in the world and so many spices that we can use, it almost feels like a bit of a cop out because it\u0026rsquo;s easy to overpower [other ingredients] with onion and garlic. But if you can learn how to cook using herbs and spices, you\u0026rsquo;ll notice you can make so many more flavours \u0026mdash; you don\u0026rsquo;t even end up needing [these two] in a lot of dishes. So it\u0026rsquo;s actually [shown] me how to become a better cook at home because I get to experiment with more flavours than just one or two that become the base of everything.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eYou also avoid alcohol. What do you turn to in place of alcoholic cocktails when the occasion calls for something a little out of the ordinary?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eA lot of my friends did drink and I wanted to create a space where coming over on a Friday night, they still had something that they can pour into a nice glass. So I just created a really simple pomegranate spritz that they could have in [their] wine glass. [You can have that] feeling of having a fancy drink, but without the hangover the next day. I started experimenting with different drinks, different tonics and non-alcoholic drinks. I\u0026rsquo;ve got a couple [of recipes] in my book, but I think \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/dry-january-non-alcoholic-alternatives/\"\u003ethere are so many different options\u003c/a\u003e that you can create without alcohol. I try different new things out with different glasses and just make it feel a bit fancy.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRelated: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/sleepy-time-mocktail/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003eSleepy Time Mocktail\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eHaving gone through the transition yourself, what advice do you have for someone adopting a more plant-based diet and lifestyle?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eI\u0026rsquo;d say one of the best things to do is every month or every week \u0026mdash; whatever feels most doable \u0026mdash; write down a list of vegetables you want to try out and base your meal around.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eSo I say trying out food and being open to experimenting is going to be key to having a meal plan. You can get stuck with so many foods that are plant-based and \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/tag/vegan/\"\u003evegan\u003c/a\u003e that aren\u0026rsquo;t actually that good for you.\u0026nbsp; More than the substitutes that exist, try out vegetables first, maybe pick a theme that you want to base your meals around in the week and try out different ways of cooking [the key ingredients], and then create your weekly meal plans from the ones that you love.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eI think we\u0026rsquo;re used to going in all or nothing, and I think taking baby steps is a way towards making a change that you can stick with.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRead More: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/miso-ginger-carrot-and-sweet-potato-soup/\"\u003eMiso Ginger Carrot and Sweet Potato Soup for Coughs and Sore Throats\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat key message do you want your readers to take away from \u003cem\u003eJOYFULL\u003c/em\u003e?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-weight: 400;\"\u003eThe whole point of this book is to bring a little bit more joy into your life. There are obviously the recipes, but then there are also so many health, wellness and mindfulness tips that not just impact the way that you\u0026rsquo;re eating, but also how you live throughout the day. I hope that the food brings you joy, but also that these incredible practices that have changed my life also have an impact [on] other people\u0026rsquo;s lives.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou May Also Like: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/sohla-el-waylly-start-here-cookbook-interview/\"\u003eSohla El-Waylly on Her New Cookbook and the Dish She\u0026rsquo;d Make to Beat Bobby Flay\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eThis interview has been edited and condensed.\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n","modified":"2024-02-26T13:41:13","date":"2024-02-27T09:00:58","uri":"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/radhi-devlukia-shetty-joyfull-interview","slug":"radhi-devlukia-shetty-joyfull-interview","featuredImage":{"__typename":"NodeWithFeaturedImageToMediaItemConnectionEdge","node":{"__typename":"MediaItem","title":"FNC feature image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty (1)","altText":"Radhi Devlukia-Shetty and her family","mediaItemUrl":"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-feature-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-1.jpg","srcSet":"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-feature-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-1.jpg 1280w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-feature-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-1.jpg?resize=300,200 300w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-feature-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-1.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-feature-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-1.jpg?resize=1024,682 1024w","sourceUrl":"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FNC-feature-image-Radhi-Devlukia-Shetty-1.jpg","caption":"Alanna Hale","mediaDetails":{"__typename":"MediaDetails","height":853,"width":1280}}},"featuredTag":{"__typename":"Post_Featuredtag","recipeDetailFeaturedTag":{"__typename":"Tag","name":"culture","slug":"culture","showTag":{"__typename":"Tag_Showtag","showTag":null},"distributions":[""]}},"tags":{"__typename":"PostToTagConnection","nodes":[{"__typename":"Tag","name":"culture","slug":"culture","distributions":[""]},{"__typename":"Tag","name":"healthy eating","slug":"healthy-eating","distributions":[""]},{"__typename":"Tag","name":"shopping","slug":"shopping","distributions":[""]},{"__typename":"Tag","name":"vegan","slug":"vegan","distributions":[""]},{"__typename":"Tag","name":"vegetarian","slug":"vegetarian","distributi